{"id":"1807.10155","submitter":"Song Shao","authors":"Wen Huang, Song Shao, Xiangdong Ye","title":"An answer to Furstenberg's problem on topological disjointness","comments":"To appear in Ergodic Theory and Dynamical Systems","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.DS","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In this paper we give an answer to Furstenberg's problem on topological\ndisjointness. Namely, we show that a transitive system $(X,T)$ is disjoint from\nall minimal systems if and only if $(X,T)$ is weakly mixing and there is some\ncountable dense subset $D$ of $X$ such that for any minimal system $(Y,S)$, any\npoint $y\\in Y$ and any open neighbourhood $V$ of $y$, and for any nonempty open\nsubset $U\\subset X$, there is $x\\in D\\cap U$ satisfying that $\\{n\\in{ \\mathbb\nZ}_+: T^nx\\in U, S^ny\\in V\\}$ is syndetic. Some characterization for the\ngeneral case is also described.\n  As applications we show that if a transitive system $(X,T)$ is disjoint from\nall minimal systems, then so are $(X^n,T^{(n)})$ and $(X, T^n)$ for any $n\\in {\n\\mathbb N}$. It turns out that a transitive system $(X,T)$ is disjoint from all\nminimal systems if and only if the hyperspace system $(K(X),T_K)$ is disjoint\nfrom all minimal systems.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 25 Jul 2018 15:47:47 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sat, 28 Jul 2018 14:49:01 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Thu, 21 Feb 2019 15:52:04 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Sat, 23 Feb 2019 16:23:20 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-02-26"}
